Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Cases heard: 14CF52 & 11CF66, Defendant Ryan D Cook in court, in custody with attorney Steven C. Mcgaver.  Jane E. Kohlwey appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Statements made by attorneys.Victim M.H. made statement.  In 14CF52, Court went over the rights & elements. Defendant plead no contest to count one. Court found defendant guilty, entered judgment, sentence withheld, 3 yr. probation, submit DNA sample, pay $250 surcharge, court costs, complete psychological evaluation and follow all treatment recommendations, no contact M.H. & A.B., their residences or workplaces or roadway outside residences, no 3rd party contact or electronic contact. Maintain absolute sobriety.  (No jail credit).  In 11CF66, Court sentenced defendant on cts. 3,4,5 to 90 days jail on each ct, consecutive to each other. Court deemed time served. (203 days jail credit).   On ct. 1, Court imposed 3 1/2 yr. prison consisting of 1 1/2 yrs. confinement, 2 yrs. extended supervision, stayed it and placed defendant on 3 yr. probation, conditions: submit DNA sample, pay $250 surcharge, $1,258 fine, complete psychological evaluation and follow all treatment recommendations, no contact M.H. & A.B., their residences or workplaces or roadway outside residences, no 3rd party contact or electronic contact. Maintain absolute sobriety. (234 days jail credit) Court denied defendant's prior motions in 11CF66.
